Logical Model: Transplant Case Logical Model

Official URL: http://example.org/fhir/ImplementationGuide/donor-ig/StructureDefinition/transplant-case Version: 0.1.0
Draft as of 2025-12-10 Computable Name: TransplantCase

High-level logical model summarising a pediatric transplant case in PROTECT-CHILD.

It connects the main clinical and data domains:

  • Recipient (PatientTransplant)
  • Donor (Donor)
  • Transplant encounter (Transplant)
  • Visits and follow-up
  • Concomitant diseases and medications
  • Immunosuppression
  • Clinical variables, labs, microbiology, instrumental investigations
  • Events and outcomes
  • Provenance / technical metadata

TransplantCase logical model

The TransplantCase logical model provides a high-level, implementation-neutral view of how this IG represents a pediatric transplant case in PROTECT-CHILD.

Example scenario

A child with a rare metabolic liver disease is referred to one of the TransplantChild ERN centres and enrolled in the PROTECT-CHILD cohort. The recipient is represented using the Transplant Recipient profile, and the donor as a Donor. The transplant admission itself is captured as a Transplant encounter linking recipient and donor, with the transplant centre and organ type recorded in a structured way.

In the months after surgery, each follow-up visit at the participating hospitals is recorded as a Visit, with routine laboratory monitoring (LabResult and LabReport), infection work-up (Microbiology observations grouped where appropriate in LabReport), and instrumental investigations through PatientInstrumentalInvestigation. Induction and maintenance immunosuppression are captured using PreMedication, ImmunosuppressiveInductionPatient, ImmunosuppressiveMaintenancePatient, and the Immunosuppressant catalog.

Across the four pilot hospitals, biospecimens from these children (e.g. blood, liver biopsy) are recorded as BioSample and linked to genomic and methylomic analyses via GenomicTest, VariantOccurrence, VariantAnnotation, EpigenomeStudy, and MethylomicStudy. Rejection episodes and other post-transplant complications are stored as PostEvent, while overall graft and patient status at key time points are captured in Outcome.

In particular:

  • recipient → Transplant Recipient (recipient patient)
  • donor → Donor (donor patient)
  • transplant → Transplant (Encounter) plus optional rejection-related PostEvent and Outcome resources
  • visits → follow-up Visit (Encounter) profiles
  • concomitant → ConcomitantDisease, ConcomitantEpisode, ConcomitantMedication
  • immunosuppression → PreMedication, ImmunosuppressiveInductionPatient, ImmunosuppressiveMaintenancePatient, and Immunosuppressant
  • clinicalData → ClinicalVariable, LabResultObservation and LabReport, Microbiology (with microbiology reports also represented using LabReport), PatientInstrumentalInvestigation
  • omics → BioSample (Specimen) and associated GenomicTest, VariantOccurrence, VariantAnnotation, EpigenomeStudy, MethylomicStudy, ReferenceGenome
  • eventsAndOutcomes → PostEvent and Outcome

This logical model is not intended for direct implementation. Instead, it serves as a narrative map that shows how the different FHIR profiles in PROTECT-CHILD fit together to represent a complete pediatric transplant case across clinical, laboratory, microbiology, biospecimen, and omics domains.

Usages:

  • This Logical Model is not used by any profiles in this Implementation Guide

You can also check for usages in the FHIR IG Statistics
